    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-06-29T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-06-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="870"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d870">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">390.1115A/1637: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Switzerland</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harrison</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bern</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-06-29">June 29,
                            1943</date>.<lb/>[Received June 30—6:57 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3587. American interest—China. Legation’s 2577, 27.<note n="75" xml:id="d870fn75"
                        >Dated April 27, not printed; for summary, see footnote 51, <ref
                            target="#pg_986">p. 986</ref>.</note> Consulate Shanghai telegraphs:
                        <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>Eight Americans interned June 17 former American Columbia Country Club
                            five others June 19 Lunghwa camp. All 13 [are] members Committee
                            American Association which therefore forced cease all activities.</p>
                        <p>All Americans residing Shanghai now interned except those oriental origin
                            and very small number exempted reasons health or other. Americans from
                            other parts occupied China especially Amoy and Ningpo arrived internment
                            camps Shanghai. Endeavoring obtain lists internees but meeting
                            considerable difficulties due especially frequent transfers one camp to
                            another and because receive no official information from Japanese
                            authorities.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harrison</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
